4 (d) Program Operations. Clinical Review Criteria, Generally. – In every utilization
5 review program, an insurer or URO shall use documented clinical review criteria that are based
6 on sound clinical evidence and that are periodically evaluated at least annually to assure ongoing
7 efficacy. An insurer may develop its own clinical review criteria or purchase or license clinical
8 review criteria. criteria, provided that the clinical review meets, at a minimum, all of the
9 following standards:
10 (1) The criteria used is based on applicable nationally recognized medical
11 standards.
12 (2) The clinical review and standards used are consistent with applicable
13 government guidelines.
14 (3) The clinical review provides for the delivery of a healthcare service in a
15 clinically appropriate type, frequency, and setting and for a clinically
16 appropriate duration.
17 (4) The criteria used in the clinical review reflects the current medical and
18 scientific evidence regarding emerging procedures, clinical guidelines, and
19 best practices, as articulated in independent, peer-reviewed medical literature.
20 (5) The clinical review is sufficiently flexible to allow deviations from the norm
21 when justified on a case-by-case basis to ensure access to care.
22 (d1) Clinical Review Criteria, Substance Use Treatment. – Criteria for determining when
23 a patient needs to be placed in a substance abuse treatment program shall be either (i) the
24 diagnostic criteria contained in the most recent revision of the American Society of Addiction
25 Medicine Patient Placement Criteria for the Treatment of Substance-Related Disorders or (ii)
26 criteria adopted by the insurer or its URO. Disorders. The Department, in consultation with the
27 Department of Health and Human Services, may require proof of compliance with this subsection
28 by a plan or URO.
29 (d2) Administration of Program. – All of the following shall apply in the administration of
30 a utilization review program under this section:
31 (1) Qualified health care professionals shall administer the utilization review
32 program and oversee review decisions under the direction of a medical doctor.
33 A medical doctor licensed to practice medicine in this State shall evaluate the
34 clinical appropriateness of noncertifications. An insurer and its URO shall
