3 (m) Disclosure of Utilization Review Requirements. – Information required to be
4 provided under this section shall be described in detail and in easily understandable language.
5 All of the following apply to an insurer's responsibility to disclose any utilization review
6 procedures:
7 (1) Coverage and member handbook. – In the certificate of coverage and member
8 handbook provided to covered persons, an insurer shall include a clear and
9 comprehensive description of its utilization review procedures, including the
10 procedures for appealing noncertifications and a statement of the rights and
11 responsibilities of covered persons, including the voluntary nature of the
12 appeal process, with respect to those procedures. An insurer shall also include
13 in the certificate of coverage and the member handbook information about the
14 availability of assistance from the Department's Health Insurance Smart NC,
15 including the telephone number and address of the Program. program.
16 (2) Prospective materials. – An insurer shall include a summary of its utilization
17 review procedures in materials intended for prospective covered persons.
18 (3) Membership cards. – An insurer shall print on its membership cards a toll-free
19 telephone number to call for utilization review purposes.
20 (4) Website. – An insurer shall make any current utilization review requirements
21 and restrictions readily accessible on its website.
22 (m1) Changes to Utilization Review. – If an insurer intends either to implement a new
23 utilization review requirement or restriction or to amend an existing requirement or restriction,
24 then all of the following apply:
25 (1) The new or amended requirement or restriction shall not be in effect unless
26 and until the insurer's website has been updated to reflect the new or amended
27 requirement or restriction. A claim shall not be denied for failure to obtain a
28 prior authorization if the new or amended requirement or restriction was not
29 in effect on the date of service of the claim.
30 (2) The insurer shall provide participating providers written notice of the new or
31 amended requirement or restriction no less than 60 calendar days before the
32 requirement or restriction is implemented.
33 This subsection does not apply if an insurer removes a utilization review requirement or
34 restriction or amends a requirement or restriction to be less restrictive.
35 (n) Maintenance of Records. – Every insurer and URO shall maintain records of each
36 review performed and each appeal received or reviewed, as well as documentation sufficient to
37 demonstrate compliance with this section. The maintenance of these records, including electronic
38 reproduction and storage, shall be governed by rules adopted by the Commissioner that apply to
39 insurers. These records shall be retained by the insurer and URO for a period of five years or, for
40 domestic companies, until the Commissioner has adopted a final report of a general examination
41 that contains a review of these records for that calendar year, whichever is later.
42 (n1) Utilization Review Statistics. – An insurer using utilization review shall make
43 statistics available regarding utilization review approvals and noncertifications on its website in
44 a readily accessible format and shall update the information available, at a minimum, on a
45 monthly basis. These statistics shall include the most recent 12-month rolling data reported
46 separately for medications and procedural codes for all of the following:
47 (1) The total number of medications and procedural codes subject to utilization
48 review, and specifically prior authorization.
49 (2) The percentage of medications and procedural codes requiring prior
50 authorization.
51 (3) The reasons for any noncertifications issued.
Page 10 DRH40233-MR-42

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) The number and percentage of utilization review determinations that are
2 appealed and the number and percentage of appeals that are approved or
3 denied at each stage of the appeal process.
4 (5) The average time and distribution by percentile of number of days between
5 submission and response of each stage of the appeal process.
6 (6) The number and percentage of providers who qualify for an exemption from
7 the utilization review process under this section.
8 (n2) Utilization Review Determination Validity. – A utilization review determination shall
9 be valid for the entire duration of the approved course of treatment and shall be effective
10 regardless of any changes in dosage for a prescription drug prescribed by a provider. If an insurer
11 requires a utilization review determination for a healthcare service for the treatment of a chronic
12 or long-term care condition, then the utilization review determination shall remain valid for the
13 length of the treatment and the insurer may not require the covered person to obtain a utilization
14 review determination again for the healthcare service.
15 (o) Violation. – A violation of this section subjects an insurer to G.S. 58-2-70.
16 (p) Continuity of Care. – The following requirements shall apply to ensure continuity of
17 care for covered persons:
18 (1) On receipt from a covered person or the covered person's provider of
19 information documenting a prior utilization review determination, an insurer
20 shall honor a utilization review determination granted to the covered person
21 from a previous insurer for at least 90 calendar days of a covered person's
22 coverage under a new health benefit plan. During this 90-day time period, an
23 insurer may perform its own utilization review.
24 (2) If the insurer makes a change in coverage of, or approval criteria for, a
25 previously authorized healthcare service, then the change in coverage or
26 approval criteria shall not affect a covered person who received a utilization
27 review determination before the effective date of the change for the remainder
28 of that covered person's health benefit plan year.
29 (3) An insurer shall continue to honor a utilization review determination that the
30 insurer or its URO certified for a covered person when that covered person
31 changes products or health benefit plans under the same insurer, provided that
32 the medically necessary services or supplies subject to the utilization review
33 determination do not change.
34 (4) If a provider performs a healthcare service that is closely related to the service
35 for which certification has already been granted by an insurer or its URO, then
36 that insurer or its URO shall not deny a claim for the closely related service
37 for failure of the provider to seek or obtain a utilization review so long as the
38 provider had notified the insurer or its URO of the performance of the closely
39 related service both no later than three business days following the completion
40 of the closely related service and prior to the submission of a claim for
41 payment for that service. The submission of the notification shall include the
42 submission of all relevant clinical information necessary for the insurer to
43 evaluate the medical necessity of the service. Nothing in this subsection shall
44 be construed to limit an insurer's retrospective review of medical necessity of
45 the closely related service nor limit the need for verification of the covered
46 person's eligibility for coverage under the health benefit plan.
47 (5) An insurer shall not restrict benefits for any hospital stay of a covered person
48 in connection with childbirth for the mother or newborn child (i) following a
49 normal vaginal delivery to less than 48 hours or (ii) following a cesarean
50 section to less than 96 hours. An insurer shall not require that a provider obtain
DRH40233-MR-42 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a utilization review determination from an insurer for prescribing the length
2 of stay required under this subdivision.
3 (q) Exemptions. – This subsection shall not apply to utilization review requests that are
4 pending review by an insurer or its URO. An insurer may not require a provider to request a
5 utilization review for a healthcare service in order for the covered person to whom the healthcare
6 service is being provided to receive coverage for the service if, within the most recent 12-month
7 period, the insurer or its URO has issued certifications, or would have issued certifications, for
8 not less than eighty percent (80%) of the utilization review requests submitted by the provider
9 for that healthcare service. An insurer may evaluate whether a provider continues to qualify for
10 this exemption not more than once every 12 months. All of the following apply to an exemption
11 under this subsection:
12 (1) A provider is not required to request an exemption in order to qualify for the
13 exemption.
14 (2) No more than once per year per healthcare service, a provider who does not
15 receive an exemption under this subsection may request from the insurer
16 evidence to support the insurer's decision. A healthcare provider may appeal
17 an insurer's decision to deny the exemption.
18 (3) An insurer may only revoke an exemption at the end of the applicable
19 12-month period if the insurer does all of the following:
20 a. Makes a determination that the provider would not have met the eighty
21 percent (80%) approval criteria based on a retrospective review of the
22 claims for the particular service for which the exemption applies for
23 the previous three months or for a longer period if needed to reach a
24 minimum of 10 claims for review.
25 b. Provides the provider with the information the insurer relied upon in
26 making the determination to revoke the exemption.
27 c. Provides the provider a plain language explanation of how to appeal
28 the decision.
29 (4) If an insurer revokes an exemption, then that exemption will remain in effect
30 until the thirtieth calendar day after the date the insurer notifies the provider
31 of its revocation of the exemption unless the provider appeals the revocation.
32 If the provider appeals the revocation, then the exemption shall remain in
33 effect until the fifth calendar day after the revocation is upheld on appeal.
34 (5) An insurer shall provide a healthcare provider that receives an exemption all
35 of the following:
36 a. A statement that the provider qualifies for an exemption from
37 preauthorization requirements.
38 b. A list of services for which the exemption applies.
39 c. A statement of the duration of the exemption.
40 (6) An insurer shall not deny or reduce payment for a healthcare service exempted
41 from a utilization review requirement under this subsection, including a
42 healthcare service performed or supervised by another provider when the
43 provider who ordered the service received an exemption, unless the rendering
44 provider meets one of the following criteria:
45 a. Knowingly and materially misrepresented the healthcare service as a
46 part of the request for payment submitted to the insurer with the
47 specific intent to deceive and obtain an unlawful payment from the
48 insurer.
49 b. Failed to substantially perform the healthcare service.
50 Nothing in this subsection requires an insurer to evaluate an existing exemption or prevents
51 an insurer from establishing a longer exemption period.
