49 PART II. ENFORCEMENT OF LICENSING REQUIREMENTS FOR HEALTH
50 INSURANCE UTILIZATION REVIEW
51 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 90-1.1(5) reads as rewritten:
DRH40233-MR-42 Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(5) The practice of medicine or surgery. – Except as otherwise provided by this
2 subdivision, the practice of medicine or surgery, for purposes of this Article,
3 includes any of the following acts:
4 …
5 g. Performing any portion of the utilization review process under
6 G.S. 58-50-51 that is required under that section to be performed by a
7 physician licensed to practice medicine, including making a final
8 utilization review decision, issuing a noncertification, and
9 participating on behalf of an insurer in the utilization reconsideration
10 and appeal process.
11 …."
12 SECTION 2.(b) Part 2 of Article 50 of Chapter 58 of the General Statues is amended
13 by adding a new section to read:
14 "§ 58-50-64. Utilization review disciplinary actions; North Carolina Medical Board.
15 (a) Performing any portion of the utilization review process under G.S. 58-50-61 that is
16 required to be performed by a licensed physician, including making a final utilization review
17 decision, issuing a noncertification, and participating on behalf of the insurer in the utilization
18 reconsideration and appeal process, is the practice of medicine under G.S. 90-1.1(5).
19 (b) The North Carolina Medical Board has the authority to subpoena an insurer, or a
20 utilization review organization acting on behalf of an insurer, for any records, documents, or
21 other materials pertaining to the involvement of any physician licensed in this State in the
22 utilization review process under G.S. 58-50-61.
23 (c) If an insurer, or a utilization review organization acting on behalf of an insurer, fails
24 to comply with a subpoena issued in accordance with this section, the North Carolina Medical
25 Board shall report the failure to comply and any information supporting the failure to the
26 Commissioner.
27 (d) Notwithstanding the penalty minimum limit under G.S. 58-2-70, the failure of an
28 insurer, or a utilization review organization acting on behalf of an insurer, to provide information
29 required by a subpoena issued in accordance with this section is a violation subjecting the insurer
30 to a fine of no less than five hundred dollars ($500.00) for each 90-day period in which the
31 information is not produced.
32 (e) If the North Carolina Medical Board takes any disciplinary action under G.S. 90-14(a)
33 against a licensed physician as a result of that physician's involvement in the utilization review
34 process under G.S. 58-50-61, then any noncertifications that were issued that are related, in whole
35 or in part, to the disciplinary action shall be subject to reconsideration or appeal under
36 G.S. 58-50-61 so long as the noncertification had not been reversed prior to the disciplinary
37 action. The North Carolina Medical Board shall notify the insurer of the disciplinary action and
38 the utilization determinations involved."
39 SECTION 2.(c) G.S. 135-48.10 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 135-48.10. Confidentiality of information and medical records; provider contracts.
41 (a) Any information described in this section that is in the possession of the State Health
42 Plan for Teachers and State Employees or its Claims Processor under the Plan or the Predecessor
43 Plan shall be confidential and shall be exempt from the provisions of Chapter 132 of the General
44 Statutes or any other provision requiring information and records held by State agencies to be
45 made public or accessible to the public. This section shall apply to all information concerning
46 individuals, including the fact of coverage or noncoverage, whether or not a claim has been filed,
47 medical information, whether or not a claim has been paid, and any other information or materials
48 concerning a plan participant, including Claim Payment Data and any documents or other
49 materials derived from the Claim Payment Data. This information may, however, be released to
50 the State Auditor or to the Auditor, the Attorney General General, or the North Carolina Medical
51 Board in furtherance of their the respective statutory duties and responsibilities, responsibilities
Page 14 DRH40233-MR-42

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of each party or to such persons or organizations as may be designated and approved by the State
2 Treasurer. Any information so that is released shall remain confidential as stated above and any
3 as stipulated by this section. Any party obtaining such information under this section shall assume
4 the same level of responsibility for maintaining such confidentiality as that of the State Health
5 Plan for Teachers and State Employees.
6 (b) The terms of a contract between the Plan and its third party administrator or between
7 the Plan and its pharmacy benefit manager are a public record under Chapter 132 of the General
8 Statutes. No provision of law, however, shall be construed to prevent or restrict the release of
9 any information in a Plan contract to the State Treasurer, the State Auditor, the Attorney General,
10 the North Carolina Medical Board, the Director of the State Budget, the Plan's Board of Trustees,
11 and the Plan's Executive Administrator solely and exclusively for their use in the furtherance of
12 their duties and responsibilities.
13 (c) Performing any portion of the utilization review process under G.S. 58-50-61 that is
14 required to be performed by a licensed physician, including making a final utilization review
15 decision, issuing a noncertification, and participating on behalf of the insurer in the utilization
16 reconsideration and appeal process, is the practice of medicine under G.S. 90-1.1(5). Subject to
17 this section, all of the following shall apply:
18 (1) The North Carolina Medical Board has the authority to subpoena the Plan, or
19 a utilization review organization acting on behalf of the Plan, for any records,
20 documents, or other materials pertaining to the involvement of any physician
21 licensed in this State in the utilization review process under the Plan.
22 (2) If the North Carolina Medical Board takes any disciplinary action under
23 G.S. 90-14(a) against a licensed physician as a result of that physician's
24 involvement in the Plan's utilization review process, then any
25 noncertifications that were issued that are related, in whole or in part, to the
26 disciplinary action shall be subject to reconsideration or appeal so long as the
27 noncertification had not been reversed prior to the disciplinary action. The
28 North Carolina Medical Board shall notify the Plan of the disciplinary action
29 and the utilization determinations involved."
